    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT326-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">ciṟaippuṟam. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Hedge. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT326">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> tuṇaitta kōtaip paṇaipperun tōḷiṉar</l>
          <l> kaṭalāṭu makaḷir kāṉa liḻaitta</l>
          <l> ciṟumaṉaip puṇarnta naṭpē tōḻi</l>
          <l> yorunāṭ ṭuṟaivaṉ ṟuṟappiṟ</l>
          <l> paṉṉāḷ varūu miṉṉā maittē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>The friendship, friend, bound in the little house</l>
          <l rend="indent2">made in the seashore grove by women playing in the sea,</l>
          <l rend="indent5">with big bamboo shoulders [and] wound garlands,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">if the man from the ghat gives [it] up for one day <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	orunāḷ </term>: or even "if the man from the ghat gives [it] up one day"? </note> </l>
          <l>is an unsweetness <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> iṉṉāmaittu </term>: the choice of this word for a predicate noun to the subject <term xml:lang="ta"> naṭpu </term> might not by chance not be one of the usual words for sorrow. The things HE does to HER are called <term xml:lang="ta"> iṉṉa </term>, the life she leads with him is her <term xml:lang="ta"> iṉṉuyir </term>, etc. </note> coming for many days.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
